 Here is an example of a Java program that reads a file and prints its content to the console:

```java
import java.io.File;
import java.io.FileNotFoundException;
import java.util.Scanner;

public class ReadFile {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Define the file path
        String filePath = "path/to/your/file.txt";

        // Create a File object
        File file = new File(filePath);

        // Create a Scanner object to read from the file
        Scanner scanner;
        try {
            scanner = new Scanner(file);

            // Read and print the content of the file
            while (scanner.hasNextLine()) {
                String line = scanner.nextLine();
                System.out.println(line);
            }

            // Close the scanner
            scanner.close();
        } catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
            System.err.println("File not found: " + filePath);
        }
    }
}
```

Replace `path/to/your/file.txt` with the actual path to your file, and when you run this program, it will read the content of the file and print each line to the console.

 Here's a simple example of a React component that meets your requirements:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';

const CounterButton = () => {
  // Initialize the count state with a value of 0
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  // Function to handle button click and increment count
  const handleClick = () => {
    setCount(count + 1);
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Counter: {count}</p>
      <button onClick={handleClick}>Increment</button>
    </div>
  );
};

export default CounterButton;
```

This component uses the `useState` hook to create a state variable called `count`. It initializes the count with a value of 0. The `handleClick` function is defined to increment the count by 1 when it's invoked, and this function is set as the `onClick` handler for the button element. The current value of the count is displayed in a paragraph element inside the `div`.

 Here is a simple C program to calculate the factorial of the number 5:

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int num = 5;
    long long factorial = 1;

    for(int i = 1; i <= num; i++) {
        factorial *= i;
    }

    printf("Factorial of %d is: %lld\n", num, factorial);

    return 0;
}
```

